      "title": "HRA Exemption 2025: How to Calculate Tax-Free House Rent Allowance",
      "excerpt": "Step-by-step guide to calculate HRA exemption with examples. Learn what documents are needed and how to maximize your tax-free HRA component.",
      "content": "<h2>What is HRA?</h2><p>House Rent Allowance (HRA) is a component of salary provided by employers to employees for meeting accommodation expenses. A portion of HRA is exempt from income tax based on specific rules.</p><h2>HRA Exemption Rules</h2><p>The exemption is the <strong>lowest</strong> of three amounts:</p><ol><li>Actual HRA received from employer</li><li>Actual rent paid minus 10% of basic salary</li><li>50% of basic salary (for metro cities) or 40% (for non-metro cities)</li></ol><h3>Metro Cities Classification</h3><p>Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, and Chennai are classified as metro cities (50% applicable). All other cities fall under non-metro category (40%).</p><h2>Example Calculations</h2><h3>Example 1: Metro City</h3><p><strong>Details:</strong></p><ul><li>Basic Salary: ₹50,000/month</li><li>HRA Received: ₹25,000/month</li><li>Rent Paid: ₹20,000/month</li><li>City: Mumbai (Metro)</li></ul><p><strong>Calculation:</strong></p><ol><li>Actual HRA: ₹25,000</li><li>Rent - 10% of basic: ₹20,000 - ₹5,000 = ₹15,000</li><li>50% of basic: ₹25,000</li></ol><p><strong>Exempt Amount:</strong> ₹15,000/month (lowest of three)</p><p><strong>Taxable HRA:</strong> ₹25,000 - ₹15,000 = ₹10,000/month</p><h3>Example 2: Non-Metro City</h3><p><strong>Details:</strong></p><ul><li>Basic Salary: ₹60,000/month</li><li>HRA Received: ₹20,000/month</li><li>Rent Paid: ₹18,000/month</li><li>City: Pune (Non-Metro)</li></ul><p><strong>Calculation:</strong></p><ol><li>Actual HRA: ₹20,000</li><li>Rent - 10% of basic: ₹18,000 - ₹6,000 = ₹12,000</li><li>40% of basic: ₹24,000</li></ol><p><strong>Exempt Amount:</strong> ₹12,000/month</p><p><strong>Taxable HRA:</strong> ₹8,000/month</p><h2>Documents Required</h2><h3>Rent Less than ₹1,00,000/year</h3><ul><li>Rent receipts (landlord signature required)</li><li>Landlord's name and address</li></ul><h3>Rent More than ₹1,00,000/year</h3><p><strong>Additional requirement:</strong> Landlord's PAN card details</p><h2>Important Points</h2><h3>Living with Parents</h3><p>Yes, you can pay rent to parents and claim HRA exemption. Parents must show this as rental income in their tax returns.</p><h3>Own House in Different City</h3><p>If you own a house in one city but work in another, you can still claim HRA exemption for rented accommodation.</p><h3>Paying Rent to Spouse</h3><p>Not allowed. HRA exemption is not available if paying rent to spouse.</p><h3>Shared Accommodation</h3><p>Each person can claim HRA proportionate to their rent share. Ensure separate rent receipts.</p><h2>HRA vs Home Loan</h2><p>You can claim both HRA exemption and home loan interest deduction simultaneously if:</p><ul><li>You live in a rented house in one city</li><li>You own a house (with loan) in another city</li></ul><h2>HRA for New Tax Regime</h2><p><strong>Important:</strong> HRA exemption is NOT available under the new tax regime. This is a major reason why old regime benefits many salaried individuals.</p><h2>Tips to Maximize HRA Benefit</h2><ol><li><strong>Optimize rent amount:</strong> Calculate ideal rent to maximize exemption without waste</li><li><strong>Start paying rent to parents:</strong> Legal and tax-efficient if parents are in lower tax bracket</li><li><strong>Maintain proper documentation:</strong> Keep all rent receipts and landlord PAN for hassle-free claims</li><li><strong>Choose old tax regime:</strong> If HRA exemption is substantial (above ₹2 lakh annually)</li></ol><h2>Calculate Your HRA Exemption</h2><p>Use our <a href='/hra-calculator'>HRA Calculator</a> to instantly calculate your tax-free HRA amount and optimize rent payments.</p><h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2><ol><li>Claiming HRA while living in own house (not allowed)</li><li>Not declaring HRA in ITR (mandatory even if fully exempt)</li><li>Missing landlord PAN for rent above ₹1 lakh</li><li>Claiming HRA under new tax regime (not applicable)</li><li>Not considering HRA when choosing tax regime</li></ol><h2>Employer's Perspective</h2><p>Employers deduct TDS after considering HRA exemption if employee submits:</p><ul><li>Rent receipts</li><li>Landlord details</li><li>Self-declaration form</li></ul><h2>Conclusion</h2><p>HRA exemption can save ₹30,000-₹1,00,000 annually in taxes. Ensure proper documentation and optimal rent structuring. Remember, this benefit is only available in the old tax regime, making it a crucial factor in regime selection.</p>",
