      "slug": "gratuity-calculation-eligibility-rules",
      "title": "Gratuity Calculation 2025: Rules, Eligibility, and Tax Treatment",
      "excerpt": "Complete guide to gratuity calculation for both government and private sector employees. Understand eligibility criteria, tax exemption limits, and payment rules.",
      "content": "<h2>What is Gratuity?</h2><p>Gratuity is a lump sum payment made by an employer to an employee as a token of appreciation for services rendered. It's a retirement benefit governed by the Payment of Gratuity Act, 1972.</p><h2>Eligibility Criteria</h2><ul><li><strong>Minimum service:</strong> 5 years of continuous service</li><li><strong>Company size:</strong> Applicable to establishments with 10 or more employees</li><li><strong>Retirement:</strong> On retirement, resignation, death, or disability</li></ul><h3>Exception to 5-Year Rule</h3><p>If employment terminates due to death or disability, gratuity is payable regardless of service period.</p><h2>Gratuity Calculation Formula</h2><h3>For Private Sector</h3><p><strong>Formula:</strong> Gratuity = (Last drawn salary × 15 × Years of service) / 26</p><p>Where:</p><ul><li>Last drawn salary = Basic + DA</li><li>15 = 15 days' salary for each completed year</li><li>26 = Average days in a month (26 working days)</li></ul><h3>For Government Employees</h3><p><strong>Formula:</strong> Gratuity = (Last drawn salary × 15 × Years of service) / 30</p><p>Note: Government uses 30 days per month (not 26)</p><h2>Calculation Examples</h2><h3>Example 1: Private Sector Employee</h3><p><strong>Details:</strong></p><ul><li>Basic Salary: ₹50,000</li><li>DA: ₹10,000</li><li>Last drawn salary: ₹60,000</li><li>Service: 20 years</li></ul><p><strong>Calculation:</strong></p><p>Gratuity = (60,000 × 15 × 20) / 26 = ₹6,92,308</p><h3>Example 2: Government Employee</h3><p><strong>Details:</strong></p><ul><li>Basic + DA: ₹80,000</li><li>Service: 30 years</li></ul><p><strong>Calculation:</strong></p><p>Gratuity = (80,000 × 15 × 30) / 30 = ₹12,00,000</p><p>Use our <a href='/gratuity-calculator'>Gratuity Calculator</a> for instant calculations.</p><h2>Maximum Gratuity Limit</h2><p><strong>Current limit:</strong> ₹20,00,000 (increased from ₹10 lakh in March 2018)</p><p>Even if calculated gratuity exceeds ₹20 lakh, only ₹20 lakh is payable under the Act. However, employers can voluntarily pay more.</p><h2>Tax Treatment of Gratuity</h2><h3>Government Employees</h3><p><strong>Fully exempt</strong> from income tax under Section 10(10)(i)</p><h3>Private Sector (Covered under Act)</h3><p>Exempt up to the <strong>least</strong> of:</p><ol><li>Actual gratuity received</li><li>₹20,00,000 (statutory limit)</li><li>Calculated gratuity: (Last salary × 15 × service years) / 26</li></ol><h3>Non-Covered Establishments</h3><p>For companies not covered under the Act:</p><p>Exempt up to least of:</p><ol><li>Actual gratuity received</li><li>₹20,00,000</li><li>(Average salary of last 10 months × service years × 1/2)</li></ol><h2>Payment Timeline</h2><p>Gratuity must be paid within <strong>30 days</strong> from the date it becomes payable. Delay attracts simple interest at the rate notified by the government.</p><h2>Forfeiture of Gratuity</h2><p>Employer can wholly or partially forfeit gratuity if:</p><ul><li>Employee's conduct causes loss, damage, or destruction of employer's property</li><li>Employee is terminated for moral turpitude (involving offense or riotous/violent behavior)</li></ul><h2>Gratuity vs Other Benefits</h2><table><tr><th>Benefit</th><th>Eligibility</th><th>Tax Treatment</th><th>Payment</th></tr><tr><td>Gratuity</td><td>5 years service</td><td>Exempt (limits apply)</td><td>At retirement</td></tr><tr><td>Provident Fund</td><td>No minimum</td><td>EEE status</td><td>At retirement</td></tr><tr><td>Pension</td><td>Varies</td><td>Fully taxable</td><td>Monthly</td></tr><tr><td>Leave Encashment</td><td>No minimum</td><td>Partially exempt</td><td>At retirement</td></tr></table><h2>Gratuity for Contractual Employees</h2><p>Contractual or fixed-term employees are also eligible for gratuity if they complete 5 years, calculated pro-rata based on actual service days.</p><h2>Nomination Process</h2><p>Employees must nominate beneficiaries who will receive gratuity in case of death. Nomination can be changed at any time during employment.</p><h2>Gratuity During Company Closure</h2><p>If company closes due to bankruptcy or liquidation, gratuity is treated as priority debt and must be paid before other creditors.</p><h2>State-wise Variations</h2><p>Some states have modified gratuity rules:</p><ul><li><strong>West Bengal:</strong> Applicable to establishments with 5+ employees</li><li><strong>Most states:</strong> Follow central Act (10+ employees)</li></ul><h2>Common Questions</h2><h3>Is Gratuity Mandatory?</h3><p>Yes, for establishments covered under the Act. It's a statutory right, not a discretionary benefit.</p><h3>Can I Withdraw Gratuity Before Retirement?</h3><p>No, except in cases of disability or terminal illness. Normal withdrawal is only at retirement/resignation after 5 years.</p><h3>What if I Resign Before 5 Years?</h3><p>No gratuity entitlement unless termination is due to death or disability. Some companies offer voluntary gratuity.</p><h2>Calculation Tips</h2><ol><li>Only Basic + DA counts, not other allowances</li><li>Part of year service rounded to nearest year (6 months or more = 1 year)</li><li>Ensure employer includes completed years correctly</li><li>Get calculation details in writing from HR</li></ol><h2>Disputes and Appeals</h2><p>If gratuity is denied or calculated incorrectly, employee can approach:</p><ol><li>Controlling Authority (within 90 days)</li><li>Labour Commissioner</li><li>Civil Court</li></ol><h2>Conclusion</h2><p>Gratuity is a valuable retirement benefit that can provide ₹5-20 lakh corpus depending on service and salary. Understanding calculation and tax treatment helps in better retirement planning. Factor gratuity into overall retirement corpus calculation alongside PF, NPS, and personal investments.</p>",
